<chapter xml:id="ch-quadrature" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
  <title>Quadrature</title>

  <introduction>
    <p>
      In this chapter, we look at the two main aspects of calculus: differentiation and integration.
    </p>

    <p>
      In the first case, we desire to know <m>f'(x)</m>, the derivative of a function <m>f</m> for some value of <m>x</m>.
      Although most functions can be easily differentiated, if it is too complicated often a numerical derivative is sought instead.
    </p>

    <p>
      In the case of integration, we generally would like to find the value of
      <me>
        \int_{a}^{b} f(x) \, dx
      </me>
      for some continuous function <m>f</m>.
      This is an important skill in that we don't need to look very far to find functions that we can't take the antiderivative of.
      In such a case, we will resort to numerical integration or quadrature.
    </p>
  </introduction>

